   <abstract>Hand-drawn map of downtown Nashville drawn in July 1856. It names the streets and indicates a few notable buildings, especially the ones damaged or destroyed by the two fires that ravaged the city in 1856.</abstract>
   <abstract>This map accompanied a letter from John Meigs, Assistant State Librarian, to Morton Boyte Howell, dated July 25, 1856. Meigs compliments Nashville's improvement over the previous two years. He comments on the new four-story buildings rising up with (East Tennessee) marble facades. Meigs then describes the fires of April and July. He explains that the courthouse, the Nashville Inn, and seven or eight stores were burned. The July fire burned Masonic Hall and eight or nine houses. Meigs tells his friend that the fire nearly burned the new First Presbyterian Church.</abstract>
